I would accept only a narrow bulk handler that preserves the single-account domain operation and adds one pure request validator plus one result aggregator. I would reject the proposed `for body.accounts { catch all; return attempted }` shortcut because it crosses the trust boundary without prevalidation, loses required per-ID outcomes, and makes side effects possible after partial malformed input.

Smallest acceptable construction:

```ts
type BulkActivateRequest = { accounts: unknown };

type ItemResult =
  | { id: string; status: "activated" }
  | { id: string; status: "already-active" }
  | { id: string; status: "not-found" }
  | { id: string; status: "unauthorized" };

type BulkActivateResponse = {
  results: ItemResult[];
  summary: {
    activated: number;
    "already-active": number;
    "not-found": number;
    unauthorized: number;
  };
};

function parseAccountIds(input: unknown): string[] {
  if (typeof input !== "object" || input === null) throw badRequest("body must be an object");
  const accounts = (input as Record<string, unknown>).accounts;
  if (!Array.isArray(accounts)) throw badRequest("accounts must be an array");
  if (accounts.length < 1 || accounts.length > 100) throw badRequest("accounts must contain 1..100 ids");

  const ids: string[] = [];
  const seen = new Set<string>();

  for (const raw of accounts) {
    if (typeof raw !== "string") throw badRequest("each account id must be a string");
    const id = raw.trim();
    if (!isValidAccountId(id)) throw badRequest(`invalid account id: ${raw}`);
    if (seen.has(id)) throw badRequest(`duplicate account id: ${id}`);
    seen.add(id);
    ids.push(id);
  }

  return ids;
}

async function bulkActivate(
  requestBody: unknown,
  actor: Actor,
  deps: { authorize: Authorize; activateOne: ActivateOne }
): Promise<BulkActivateResponse> {
  const ids = parseAccountIds(requestBody); // reject before side effects

  const results: ItemResult[] = [];

  for (const id of ids) {
    const allowed = await deps.authorize(actor, id);
    if (!allowed) {
      results.push({ id, status: "unauthorized" });
      continue;
    }

    const outcome = await deps.activateOne(id);
    results.push({ id, status: outcome });
  }

  return {
    results,
    summary: {
      activated: results.filter(r => r.status === "activated").length,
      "already-active": results.filter(r => r.status === "already-active").length,
      "not-found": results.filter(r => r.status === "not-found").length,
      unauthorized: results.filter(r => r.status === "unauthorized").length,
    },
  };
}
```

Why this is the minimum:
- Validation is complete and front-loaded at the trust boundary. No collaborator is called until shape, count, uniqueness, and ID format are all valid.
- Authorization is evaluated per account, as required.
- Item statuses are exactly the required public outcomes. No broad exception flattening.
- Summary is mechanically derived from `results`, so it cannot drift.
- The existing single-account activation logic stays behind `activateOne`; bulk orchestration does not duplicate domain behavior.

Focused tests I would require before accepting:
- Rejects non-object body, missing `accounts`, non-array `accounts`, empty array, `>100` items.
- Rejects non-string ID, malformed ID, duplicate ID, and verifies zero calls to authorization/persistence/audit on those failures.
- Returns one result per valid input ID in input order.
- Produces `unauthorized` for an auth denial and does not call activation for that ID.
- Maps typed activation outcomes to `activated`, `already-active`, and `not-found` exactly.
- Summary counts equal the counts in `results`, not an independently maintained value.
- Mixed case test: one activated, one already active, one not found, one unauthorized, with exact result list and summary.

That is the furthest I would compress it without violating the specification.
